13.3 Manipulating Data with dplyr
dplyr provides a set of functions for common data manipulation tasks. These functions are designed to be used with the pipe operator |&gt;, which passes the output of one function as the input to the next:
Select columns:
data |&gt;
  select(student_id, grade, sel_total_mean)
Filter rows:
data |&gt;
  filter(grade == 3)

data |&gt;
  filter(grade &gt;= 3 & sel_total_mean &gt; 2.5)
Create or recode variables:
data |&gt;
  mutate(
    sel_total_z = scale(sel_total_mean),
    grade_cat = if_else(grade &lt;= 2, "lower", "upper")
  )
Summarize data:
data |&gt;
  summarise(
    n = n(),
    mean_sel = mean(sel_total_mean, na.rm = TRUE),
    sd_sel = sd(sel_total_mean, na.rm = TRUE)
  )
Group and summarize:
data |&gt;
  group_by(grade) |&gt;
  summarise(
    n = n(),
    mean_sel = mean(sel_total_mean, na.rm = TRUE)
  )

13.4 Handling Missing Data
Before any analysis, recode CWER missing data codes to NA:
data &lt;- data |&gt;
  mutate(across(everything(), ~ if_else(. %in% c(-99, -98, -97, -96), NA, .)))
Always check for missing values after recoding:
data |&gt;
  summarise(across(everything(), ~ sum(is.na(.)))) |&gt;
  pivot_longer(everything(), names_to = "variable", values_to = "n_missing") |&gt;
  filter(n_missing &gt; 0)
Flag any variables with more than 10% missing for discussion with Mike or Joanna before proceeding with analysis.

17.1.1 Basic Mplus CFA Syntax
TITLE:    CFA - SEL three-factor model

DATA:
  FILE = wave1_data.dat;

VARIABLE:
  NAMES = stuid schlid selsm1 selsm2 selsm3 selsm4
          selsa1 selsa2 selsa3 selrs1 selrs2 selrs3;
  USEVARIABLES = selsm1-selsm4 selsa1-selsa3 selrs1-selrs3;
  MISSING = ALL(-99 -98 -97 -96);
  CLUSTER = schlid;

ANALYSIS:
  TYPE = COMPLEX;
  ESTIMATOR = WLSMV;

MODEL:
  selfmgmt BY selsm1 selsm2 selsm3 selsm4;
  socaware BY selsa1 selsa2 selsa3;
  relskill BY selrs1 selrs2 selrs3;

OUTPUT:
  SAMPSTAT;
  STDYX;
  MODINDICES(10);
  FIT;


17.1.2 Key Syntax Elements
CLUSTER — specifies the clustering variable (e.g., school ID) when data are nested. Used with TYPE = COMPLEX to produce corrected standard errors.
TYPE = COMPLEX — accounts for non-independence due to clustering. Use whenever students are nested in classrooms or schools.
ESTIMATOR = WLSMV — recommended for ordinal (Likert) outcomes. Use MLR for continuous outcomes.
BY — defines the factor structure. selfmgmt BY selsm1 selsm2 selsm3 selsm4 means the factor selfmgmt is measured by those four indicators.
STDYX — requests fully standardized output, including standardized factor loadings.
MODINDICES(10) — requests modification indices greater than 10, which can help identify sources of misfit.


17.1.3 Interpreting CFA Output
After running the model, check the following in order:

Model fit — CFI, TLI, RMSEA, SRMR (see fit guidelines in the Mplus chapter)
Factor loadings — standardized loadings (STDYX) should generally be .40 or higher
Modification indices — large MIs suggest areas of misfit; consider theoretically motivated modifications
Factor correlations — very high correlations (&gt; .85) between factors may indicate discriminant validity problems



17.1.4 Higher-Order CFA
To specify a second-order factor (e.g., a general SEL factor underlying the three subscales):
MODEL:
  selfmgmt BY selsm1 selsm2 selsm3 selsm4;
  socaware BY selsa1 selsa2 selsa3;
  relskill BY selrs1 selrs2 selrs3;
  sel BY selfmgmt socaware relskill;


17.1.5 Bifactor CFA with Mplus
To specify a bifactor model (general factor + specific factors):
MODEL:
  sel BY selsm1 selsm2 selsm3 selsm4
         selsa1 selsa2 selsa3
         selrs1 selrs2 selrs3;
  selfmgmt BY selsm1 selsm2 selsm3 selsm4;
  socaware BY selsa1 selsa2 selsa3;
  relskill BY selrs1 selrs2 selrs3;

  sel WITH selfmgmt@0;
  sel WITH socaware@0;
  sel WITH relskill@0;
  selfmgmt WITH socaware@0;
  selfmgmt WITH relskill@0;
  socaware WITH relskill@0;
The @0 fixes the correlation between factors to zero, which is required for a bifactor model.

17.2 Exploratory Factor Analysis (EFA) with Mplus
EFA is used when the factor structure is unknown or you want to explore how many factors underlie a set of items. Unlike CFA, EFA does not fix items to specific factors — it allows all items to load on all factors.

17.2.1 Basic EFA Syntax with Mplus
TITLE:    EFA - SEL items

DATA:
  FILE = wave1_data.dat;

VARIABLE:
  NAMES = selsm1 selsm2 selsm3 selsm4
          selsa1 selsa2 selsa3
          selrs1 selrs2 selrs3;
  USEVARIABLES = selsm1-selsm4 selsa1-selsa3 selrs1-selrs3;
  MISSING = ALL(-99 -98 -97 -96);

ANALYSIS:
  TYPE = EFA 1 4;
  ESTIMATOR = WLSMV;
  ROTATION = GEOMIN;

OUTPUT:
  STDYX;
TYPE = EFA 1 4 tells Mplus to extract and compare solutions from 1 to 4 factors. Review the fit indices and interpretability of each solution to determine the best number of factors.
ROTATION = GEOMIN — an oblique rotation that allows factors to correlate. Preferred over orthogonal rotations (like varimax) for most psychological constructs, which are rarely truly independent.


17.2.2 Deciding on the Number of Factors
Use multiple criteria:

Fit indices — look for acceptable CFI, TLI, RMSEA across solutions
Eigenvalues — factors with eigenvalues &gt; 1 are traditionally retained, though this rule alone is insufficient
Interpretability — the factor solution should make theoretical sense
Parsimony — prefer fewer factors when fit is similar across solutions



17.2.3 ESEM with Mplus
Exploratory Structural Equation Modeling (ESEM) combines CFA and EFA — items are primarily associated with one factor but allowed to have small cross-loadings on other factors. This is often more realistic than pure CFA and produces better fit in psychological data:
ANALYSIS:
  TYPE = EFA 3 3;
  ESTIMATOR = WLSMV;
  ROTATION = TARGET;

MODEL:
  ! Target rotation specifying expected primary loadings
  f1 BY selsm1~1 selsm2~1 selsm3~1 selsm4~1
        selsa1~0 selsa2~0 selsa3~0
        selrs1~0 selrs2~0 selrs3~0;
  f2 BY selsm1~0 selsm2~0 selsm3~0 selsm4~0
        selsa1~1 selsa2~1 selsa3~1
        selrs1~0 selrs2~0 selrs3~0;
  f3 BY selsm1~0 selsm2~0 selsm3~0 selsm4~0
        selsa1~0 selsa2~0 selsa3~0
        selrs1~1 selrs2~1 selrs3~1;
~1 indicates a target loading of 1 (item primarily loads on this factor) and ~0 indicates a target of 0 (item expected to have near-zero loading on this factor).

19.2 Path Analysis in Mplus

19.2.1 Basic Path Analysis Syntax
TITLE:    Path analysis - PD to teacher practices to student outcomes

DATA:
  FILE = wave1_data.dat;

VARIABLE:
  NAMES = schlid tchrid stuid pd_hrs tch_sel stu_sel grd;
  USEVARIABLES = pd_hrs tch_sel stu_sel grd;
  MISSING = ALL(-99 -98 -97 -96);
  CLUSTER = schlid;

ANALYSIS:
  TYPE = COMPLEX;
  ESTIMATOR = MLR;

MODEL:
  ! Teacher SEL practices predicted by PD hours
  tch_sel ON pd_hrs;

  ! Student SEL predicted by teacher practices and grade
  stu_sel ON tch_sel grd;

OUTPUT:
  STDYX;
  CINTERVAL;
The ON statement specifies regression paths. stu_sel ON tch_sel grd means student SEL is regressed on teacher SEL practices and grade.


19.2.2 Mediation Analysis
To test mediation (whether the effect of X on Y operates through M), define the indirect effect using MODEL INDIRECT or MODEL CONSTRAINT:
TITLE:    Mediation - PD -&gt; teacher SEL -&gt; student SEL

DATA:
  FILE = wave1_data.dat;

VARIABLE:
  NAMES = schlid pd_hrs tch_sel stu_sel;
  USEVARIABLES = pd_hrs tch_sel stu_sel;
  MISSING = ALL(-99 -98 -97 -96);
  CLUSTER = schlid;

ANALYSIS:
  TYPE = COMPLEX;
  ESTIMATOR = MLR;
  BOOTSTRAP = 1000;

MODEL:
  tch_sel ON pd_hrs (a);
  stu_sel ON tch_sel (b);
  stu_sel ON pd_hrs (c);

MODEL CONSTRAINT:
  NEW(indirect direct total);
  indirect = a*b;
  direct = c;
  total = a*b + c;

OUTPUT:
  STDYX;
  CINTERVAL(BCBOOTSTRAP);
BOOTSTRAP = 1000 — requests 1000 bootstrap samples for confidence intervals. Required for bias-corrected bootstrap CIs on indirect effects.
MODEL CONSTRAINT — defines new parameters (here: indirect, direct, and total effects) as functions of labeled parameters.
CINTERVAL(BCBOOTSTRAP) — requests bias-corrected bootstrap confidence intervals, which are preferred over the Sobel test for testing mediation.


19.2.3 Multiple Mediators
For parallel mediation (multiple mediators operating simultaneously):
MODEL:
  med1 ON x (a1);
  med2 ON x (a2);
  y ON med1 (b1);
  y ON med2 (b2);
  y ON x (c);

MODEL CONSTRAINT:
  NEW(ind1 ind2 total_ind total);
  ind1 = a1*b1;
  ind2 = a2*b2;
  total_ind = a1*b1 + a2*b2;
  total = a1*b1 + a2*b2 + c;


19.2.4 Moderation (Interaction Effects)
To test whether the effect of X on Y differs by a moderator W, create an interaction term in R before running the model:
data_mplus &lt;- data_mplus |&gt;
  mutate(xw = x_var * w_var)
Then include the interaction term in the Mplus syntax:
MODEL:
  y ON x w xw;
The coefficient for xw is the interaction effect. If significant, the effect of X on Y depends on the value of W.


19.2.5 Running Path Analysis via MplusAutomation
library(tidyverse)
library(here)
library(MplusAutomation)

# 1. Load data
data &lt;- readRDS(here("data", "cleaned", "wave1_cleaned.rds"))

# 2. Create interaction term if needed
data &lt;- data |&gt;
  mutate(pd_sel_int = pd_hrs * tch_sel_baseline)

# 3. Rename to Mplus-compatible names
data_mplus &lt;- data |&gt;
  rename(
    schlid  = school_id,
    tchrid  = teacher_id,
    pdhrs   = pd_hrs,
    tchsel  = tch_sel,
    stusel  = stu_sel_mean,
    grd     = grade
  )

# 4. Write data file
prepareMplusData(
  data_mplus,
  filename = here("code", "mplus", "wave1_data.dat")
)

# 5. Run model
runModels(here("code", "mplus", "path_model.inp"))

# 6. Read results
output &lt;- readModels(here("code", "mplus", "path_model.out"))

# 7. Extract fit indices
fit &lt;- output$summaries |&gt;
  select(CFI, TLI, RMSEA_Estimate, SRMR)

# 8. Extract path coefficients
paths &lt;- output$parameters$stdyx.standardized

# 9. Extract indirect effects
indirect &lt;- output$parameters$indirect

# 10. Save
write_csv(fit, here("output", "tables", "path_fit.csv"))
write_csv(paths, here("output", "tables", "path_coefficients.csv"))
write_csv(indirect, here("output", "tables", "indirect_effects.csv"))


19.2.6 Model Fit for Path Models
Path models are evaluated using the same fit indices as CFA (see the Mplus chapter). A just-identified model (where the number of estimated parameters equals the number of knowns) will always fit perfectly — you need at least one degree of freedom for fit to be meaningful.
When a path model fits poorly, examine the modification indices to identify which paths might improve fit. Add paths only if they are theoretically justified — do not add paths purely to improve fit statistics.


19.2.7 Reporting Path Analysis Results
A complete report of path analysis results should include:

Sample size and missing data handling approach
Estimator used and justification
Model fit indices (CFI, TLI, RMSEA, SRMR) with confidence intervals for RMSEA
Table of path coefficients (unstandardized and standardized) with standard errors and p-values
For mediation: indirect effects with bootstrap confidence intervals
A path diagram if the model is complex enough to benefit from visual representation

20.3 IRT in Mplus

20.3.1 Binary IRT: 2PL Model
TITLE:    2PL IRT model

DATA:
  FILE = wave1_data.dat;

VARIABLE:
  NAMES = stuid item1-item10;
  USEVARIABLES = item1-item10;
  CATEGORICAL = item1-item10;
  MISSING = ALL(-99 -98 -97 -96);

ANALYSIS:
  TYPE = EFA 1 1;
  ESTIMATOR = WLSMV;
  PARAMETERIZATION = THETA;

MODEL:
  f BY item1-item10*;
  f@1;

OUTPUT:
  STDYX;
  TECH1;
  TECH4;
CATEGORICAL — tells Mplus the items are categorical (binary or ordinal). Required for IRT models.
PARAMETERIZATION = THETA — uses the IRT parameterization, which produces item discrimination (a) and difficulty (b) parameters directly. Without this, Mplus uses the default factor analytic parameterization.
TYPE = EFA 1 1 — fits a one-factor EFA, which is equivalent to a unidimensional IRT model.


20.3.2 Polytomous IRT: Graded Response Model
For Likert-scale items, the Graded Response Model estimates a discrimination parameter and multiple threshold parameters (one for each category boundary):
TITLE:    Graded Response Model

DATA:
  FILE = wave1_data.dat;

VARIABLE:
  NAMES = stuid item1-item10;
  USEVARIABLES = item1-item10;
  CATEGORICAL = item1-item10;
  MISSING = ALL(-99 -98 -97 -96);

ANALYSIS:
  ESTIMATOR = WLSMV;
  PARAMETERIZATION = THETA;

MODEL:
  f BY item1-item10*;
  f@1;

OUTPUT:
  STDYX;
  TECH1;
The output will include discrimination parameters (equivalent to factor loadings in STDYX output) and threshold parameters (equivalent to item difficulty at each category boundary).


20.3.3 Interpreting IRT Output with PARAMETERIZATION = THETA
With PARAMETERIZATION = THETA, the Mplus output provides:

Factor loadings in the MODEL RESULTS section correspond to item discriminations (a parameters). Higher values indicate better-discriminating items.
Thresholds correspond to item difficulty parameters (b parameters). For a 5-point Likert item, there are 4 thresholds representing the boundaries between response categories.
STDYX standardized loadings give the discrimination in a standardized metric comparable across items.

General guidelines for interpreting discrimination parameters:



Discrimination
Interpretation




&lt; 0.50
Poor — item provides little information


0.50–1.00
Moderate


1.00–2.00
Good


&gt; 2.00
Very high





20.3.4 Differential Item Functioning (DIF)
DIF occurs when an item functions differently for different groups (e.g., by gender or race/ethnicity) after controlling for the latent trait. DIF analysis is important for establishing measurement fairness.
To test DIF in Mplus, use multiple-group CFA with measurement invariance tests — a constrained baseline model where item parameters are equal across groups is compared to a model where parameters are freed:
TITLE:    DIF analysis - gender

DATA:
  FILE = wave1_data.dat;

VARIABLE:
  NAMES = stuid gender item1-item10;
  USEVARIABLES = item1-item10;
  CATEGORICAL = item1-item10;
  GROUPING = gender (0=male 1=female);
  MISSING = ALL(-99 -98 -97 -96);

ANALYSIS:
  ESTIMATOR = WLSMV;
  PARAMETERIZATION = THETA;

MODEL:
  f BY item1-item10*;
  f@1;

MODEL female:
  [item1$1 item1$2 item1$3 item1$4];

OUTPUT:
  STDYX;
  MODINDICES(10);
The MODEL female: section frees the thresholds for item1 in the female group, testing whether that item’s difficulty parameters differ by gender. Items showing significant DIF should be examined carefully and may need to be revised or dropped.


20.3.5 Test Information Function
The Test Information Function (TIF) shows how precisely the scale measures the latent trait at different points along the trait continuum. A well-designed scale has high information in the range of the trait most relevant to your research question.
To obtain the TIF, request PLOT2 in the OUTPUT section and use Mplus’s graphical output. With MplusAutomation, you can extract and plot item information curves in R using the mirt package, which provides more flexible IRT visualization than Mplus.


20.3.6 Running IRT via MplusAutomation
library(tidyverse)
library(here)
library(MplusAutomation)

# 1. Load data
data &lt;- readRDS(here("data", "cleaned", "wave1_cleaned.rds"))

# 2. Rename to Mplus-compatible names
data_mplus &lt;- data |&gt;
  rename(
    stuid  = student_id,
    item1  = sel_item_1,
    item2  = sel_item_2,
    item3  = sel_item_3,
    item4  = sel_item_4,
    item5  = sel_item_5,
    item6  = sel_item_6,
    item7  = sel_item_7,
    item8  = sel_item_8,
    item9  = sel_item_9,
    item10 = sel_item_10
  )

# 3. Write data file
prepareMplusData(
  data_mplus,
  filename = here("code", "mplus", "wave1_data.dat")
)

# 4. Run model
runModels(here("code", "mplus", "irt_grm.inp"))

# 5. Read results
output &lt;- readModels(here("code", "mplus", "irt_grm.out"))

# 6. Extract discrimination parameters (factor loadings)
discriminations &lt;- output$parameters$stdyx.standardized |&gt;
  filter(grepl("BY", paramHeader)) |&gt;
  select(param, est, se, est_se, pval)

# 7. Extract threshold parameters (difficulty)
thresholds &lt;- output$parameters$unstandardized |&gt;
  filter(grepl("\\$", paramHeader)) |&gt;
  select(paramHeader, param, est, se)

# 8. Save
write_csv(discriminations, here("output", "tables", "irt_discriminations.csv"))
write_csv(thresholds, here("output", "tables", "irt_thresholds.csv"))


20.3.7 Reporting IRT Results
A complete report of IRT analysis should include:

The IRT model used and justification
Estimator and software
Item discrimination parameters with standard errors for all items
Item difficulty (threshold) parameters for all items
Model fit indices
Test or scale information function
Any items flagged for poor fit, low discrimination, or DIF
Decision about item retention or revision based on IRT results

21.2 Monte Carlo Simulation in Mplus

21.2.1 Basic Monte Carlo Syntax
The following example estimates power for a CFA model with one factor and six indicators:
TITLE:    Monte Carlo - CFA power analysis

MONTECARLO:
  NAMES = y1 y2 y3 y4 y5 y6;
  NOBS = 200;
  NREP = 1000;
  SEED = 12345;

MODEL POPULATION:
  f BY y1*0.70 y2*0.65 y3*0.70 y4*0.65 y5*0.60 y6*0.65;
  f@1;
  y1-y6*0.51;

MODEL:
  f BY y1*0.70 y2*0.65 y3*0.70 y4*0.65 y5*0.60 y6*0.65;
  f@1;
  y1-y6*0.51;

OUTPUT:
  TECH9;

21.2.1.1 Key Syntax Elements
MONTECARLO — replaces the DATA section; specifies simulation parameters instead of a data file.
NOBS — sample size to simulate. Run multiple analyses at different sample sizes to find where power reaches .80.
NREP — number of replications. 1000 is a reasonable starting point; 10000 gives more stable estimates.
SEED — random seed for reproducibility. Always set a seed so results can be replicated.
MODEL POPULATION — the “true” population model used to generate data. Specify parameter values based on theory, prior research, or pilot data.
MODEL — the analysis model fit to each generated dataset. Usually matches MODEL POPULATION, but can differ to test robustness.
TECH9 — requests information about any convergence failures across replications.

21.3 Specifying Population Parameter Values
The quality of a Monte Carlo analysis depends entirely on how well your population parameter values reflect reality. Sources for these values:

Prior research — meta-analyses or studies on similar constructs and populations
Pilot data — if you have preliminary data, use it to estimate parameters
Theory — for completely novel studies, use theory to set plausible bounds and run sensitivity analyses across a range of values

For CFA, the key parameters are factor loadings and residual variances. If you specify a standardized loading of .70, the residual variance for that indicator is 1 - .70² = .51.

21.3.1 Power Analysis for Regression and Path Models
For a path model testing whether professional development predicts teacher SEL practices:
TITLE:    Monte Carlo - Path model power analysis

MONTECARLO:
  NAMES = pd tchsel stusel;
  NOBS = 150;
  NREP = 1000;
  SEED = 54321;

MODEL POPULATION:
  tchsel ON pd*0.30;
  stusel ON tchsel*0.35 pd*0.10;
  pd*1.00;
  tchsel*0.91;
  stusel*0.87;

MODEL:
  tchsel ON pd;
  stusel ON tchsel pd;

OUTPUT:
  TECH9;
The asterisked values are population parameters. Here tchsel ON pd*0.30 specifies that the path from PD to teacher SEL has a population value of 0.30 (standardized).


21.3.2 Power Analysis for Indirect Effects
To estimate power for a mediated (indirect) effect:
TITLE:    Monte Carlo - Mediation power analysis

MONTECARLO:
  NAMES = x m y;
  NOBS = 200;
  NREP = 1000;
  SEED = 99999;

MODEL POPULATION:
  m ON x*0.40;
  y ON m*0.35 x*0.15;
  x*1.00;
  m*0.84;
  y*0.84;

MODEL:
  m ON x (a);
  y ON m (b);
  y ON x;

MODEL CONSTRAINT:
  NEW(indirect);
  indirect = a*b;

OUTPUT:
  TECH9;
The power for the indirect effect is reported in the output as the proportion of replications in which indirect is significant.


21.3.3 Accounting for Missing Data
To simulate power under planned missing data designs (e.g., a three-form design) or anticipated attrition:
MONTECARLO:
  NAMES = y1 y2 y3 y4 y5 y6;
  NOBS = 250;
  NREP = 1000;
  SEED = 12345;
  PATMISS = y1(0.10) y2(0.10) y3(0.20) y4(0.20);
  PATPROB = 1.0;
PATMISS specifies the proportion of missing data for each variable. This allows you to estimate power under realistic attrition scenarios.


21.3.4 Running Monte Carlo via MplusAutomation
Monte Carlo analyses can be run from R using the same runModels() and readModels() workflow:
library(tidyverse)
library(here)
library(MplusAutomation)

# Run the Monte Carlo simulation
runModels(here("code", "mplus", "montecarlo_cfa.inp"))

# Read results
mc_output &lt;- readModels(here("code", "mplus", "montecarlo_cfa.out"))

# Extract power estimates
# Power is in the parameters section - look for the "Sig" column
power &lt;- mc_output$parameters$unstandardized |&gt;
  select(paramHeader, param, pct_sig_coef)

print(power)
The pct_sig_coef column gives the proportion of replications in which each parameter was statistically significant — this is your power estimate.


21.3.5 Finding the Required Sample Size
Run the same model at multiple sample sizes and plot power as a function of N:
# Define sample sizes to test
sample_sizes &lt;- c(50, 100, 150, 200, 250, 300)

# Run models at each N
# (assumes you have separate .inp files for each N, or modify programmatically)
results &lt;- map_dfr(sample_sizes, function(n) {
  # Read the output for this N
  output &lt;- readModels(here("code", "mplus", paste0("mc_n", n, ".out")))

  # Extract power for the parameter of interest
  power &lt;- output$parameters$unstandardized |&gt;
    filter(param == "TCHSEL") |&gt;
    pull(pct_sig_coef)

  tibble(n = n, power = power)
})

# Plot
ggplot(results, aes(x = n, y = power)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_point() +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0.80, linetype = "dashed", color = "red") +
  labs(
    x = "Sample Size",
    y = "Power",
    title = "Power as a Function of Sample Size"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

ggsave(here("output", "figures", "power_curve.png"), width = 6, height = 4, dpi = 300)


21.3.6 Reporting Monte Carlo Results
A complete report of Monte Carlo power analysis should include:

The model tested and rationale for parameter values
Sources for population parameter estimates (prior research, pilot data)
Number of replications and random seed
Power estimates for all key parameters at the chosen sample size
A power curve showing how power varies with sample size
Any convergence issues (from TECH9 output)
Sensitivity analyses if parameter estimates are uncertain
